<br>
For starters I dont think the idea of a raid enforcer is that great of an idea.  In theory of course it is good, however these things are like communism, they just dont seem to work out in real life.  Anyone that knows me would know that I am a firm believer of discipline.  With the high level raids thats all that keeps the raid alive.  Now one problem is just that the raid enforcer would not have any real power short of telling someone they cant lotto.  I say this because it still rely's on that group's leader to kick the offending person out if it is so called for.  You're just adding in another layer of red tape here.  Raid enforcement in my opinion should be done by the group leaders with a final decision up to the Raid Commander, or maybe more likely the Vice Raid Commander.  Of course, this also has its disadvantages in that you now need 6-8 people who can keep control of their groups.  Not exactly the easiest, but I think we do have that number of people.<br>
<br>
Now the main problem is still discipline.  And the Raid Commanders having to repeat themselves multiple times is not a good thing.  What we need is not a Raid Enforcer but rather more like a guild enforcer.  What I think a lot of people forget is that especially on CoG raids you are not just representing yourself but your entire guild.  Your actions can impact other's feelings and thoughts about your guild and I think its high time we do something about it.  If guild members fail to listen to the Raid Commander on any raid then not only do we warn/disband/not allow that person to lotto for that raid, but also inform on this board and ingame that player's guild leaders and CoG representative.  If they fail to take action or they screw up on another raid (not just the next one) measures should be taken against that guild.  From not allowing the entire guild to attend or lotto on that raid to fully banning that guild from CoG raids for a specified time.  And of course if you dont have a guild you get your three warnings then appropriate measures are taken.  This seems harsh and perhaps even partially against what Haemish wanted for CoG, however, these measures are needed if CoG wishes to continue raiding.<br>
<br>
I say this because the game has changed since CoG first started.  A year ago Plane and Dragon raids were the end game.  These things were pretty much the biggest things a guild or alliance or group could do.  The only other large multi group target would probably have been the efreeti in SolB.  Then Kunark came out and raised the bar a bit.  The Kunark dragons are even harder and use different stratagies.  Many zones became raid oriented and pick up groups there non-existant.  Finally we have Velious.  Forget finding a group in the Dragon Necropolis or Sirens Grotto or Velk's Lab.  These zones are totally raid oriented and its bring your own group.  To do half or more of the zones outside of the Old World you need 30-60 level 50+ people all working together.  Failure can mean massive wipeouts that take hours to recover from.  You do not want to wipe out in the Halls of Testing in the Temple of Veeshan for example.  The game has changed and now the Plane Raids and Old World Dragon Raids are just the begining of your raiding career.  If people cannot show the discipline and courage on these raids there's no way they can go on other higher end raids.  And believe me most Epic mobs are easier than whats lurking in the shadows in Velious.<br>
<br>
This is not to say CoG cannot do these raids.   Zellex regularly does pickup raids to DN.  About once or twice a week in fact with generally only a couple of groups.  He has proven that if a group has discipline and they are willing to die once or twice in pursuit of a sucessful raid then you dont need &quot;Perfect&quot; groups and you dont need to be lvl 55+ to be in many of these places.  Its all about discipline, courage, and a willingness to do new things and try new stratagies not for the good loot, not because its efficent or because you want a lot of xp, instead it's all about having fun and doing something other than camping LGuk or Karnors or Old Seb.  There is no prize for being 55+ or being the first in your guild to level 60.  I will honestly rather have a lvl38 cleric with just revive who knows what they're doing on a raid than a level 60 with a rez stick that thinks the rules dont apply to them.<br>
<br>
In the event this post has gone on quite long enough.  The main point is we dont need a Raid Enforcer nor does the Raid Commander have to be a dictator and the Right Hand of Innoruk.  We need group leaders who know what they're doing and we need group members that will do as they're told.  If necessary they get their three strikes then they and or their guild suffer the consequences.  I would not want to see this happen.  CoG Raid Commanders should not have to implement any kind of discipline rules.  But we will never be able to continue to the higher end raids if we dont have better discipline.  It comes down often not to the skills and leadership abilities of our Leaders but rather the discipline, Vision, and courage of our raiding party members.  To use a cliche you are the weakest link.  We should all be having fun, whether just a party member, a group leader, or a raid commander.  And if people refuse to listen and refuse to learn then eventually we will stop having these raids since the leadership will not put up with this level of stress indefinitly.  In the end its all up to each and everyone to rise above themselves and think of others instead of just themselves or their group.<br>
