s to offset the disadvantage of an additional channel to monitor as well as the possibility that you'll end up using less experienced people for group leaders just because they're in the same guild as you.  Diversity of experience is a good thing, and as I said one of CoG's biggest advantages.  No other guild or alliance on the server can potentially match CoG in the numbers it can draw or the skilled people.  And I believe giving those same skilled people leadership responsibilities will help draw them back which will only strength future raids.<br>
<br>
And experienced and good group leaders would seem to me to obliviate the need for a Raid Enforcer.  All problems are then handled within the group and then kicked up to the Raid Commander for final decisions if needed.  Unity of spirit and purpose comes from within small unit organization.  It cannot be imposed from the outside in my opinion.  Micromanagement of the leadership will only result in more hassles and less efficency.  Choose good leaders, give them responsibilities, and let them go.  All the Raid Enforcer would do is to do the job of the group leaders in maintaining order, except they would have to handle upwards of 60 people instead of just 6.  It would also mean group leaders would not have much to do besides form the group.  This will not help the overall goal of growing new leaders by giving them responsibilities on raids.  In order to hit the larger targets CoG's discipline must get stronger and you do that by growing leaders who understand their responsibilities to a raid, not by becoming a dictator and telling everyone to step first with the left foot.   <br>
<br>
As for guild responsibility that kinda worries me too.  But in the end something has to happen.  Guilds will be allowed the chance to fix any problems.  If its only 1 or 2 bad apples the guild should be able to either talk to them, or in extreme situations boot them from the guild.  We have guild representatives here with email addresses, reporting problems should not be a difficult task, distasteful tho it might be.  Failure of a guild to respond to our concerns would indicate to me an unwillingness to play by the rules that bind the rest of us.  Which in turn would indicate that the problem goes beyond just a few members of that guild.  And I would note that under this system those of us who are not guilded have even less chances.  Because we have no guild, messing up a three or four times will result in suspension without any more chances.  A guild is supposed to be more than just a powertrip and a system for powerleveling.  There are distinct advantages and privlages that come with being in a guild, and with those perks comes responsibilities.  All the guilds who have joined CoG have agreed to the principles behind CoG.  It becomes their responsiblity to enforce that on their members or face the consequences.  CoG is not an enforement body, therefore enforcement must devolve to the individual guilds that make it up.  If a guild is willing to allow its members to consistantly endanger a entire raiding party and claim its not their fault or fail to do anything about it then they need to seriously re-evaluate their role in CoG and indeed in any alliance they may be in.<br>
