<br>
To me a raid enforcer would be more of a taddytale position so I can keep track of who is doing what. I cant be everywhere and see everything and group leaders dont always have the &quot;infulence&quot; to control a group even if they try OR, they try and deal with it and it doesn't get to the commanders attention (this one happens more often that not so I never know who to watch). Anyone thats sent me a tell durring a raid can attest that it usually takes me a while to respond, I'm not necessarily a fast typer and I stare at the keyboard so I have to constantly scroll back up.<br>
<br>
Group Leader wise - for me personally I choose group leaders that I know have experience where we are going, preferably FoF yes, but not a requirement. I know the limits of my mates just as they know me and I wont ask them to do something they dont feel they are ready for. At the same time there are a few of you out there that I trust implicitly to do what I need on time and thats why you have been asked to fill positions here and there. I would not hesitate at any time to choose any of you again.<br>
<br>
Guilds Responsibility - possibly yes possibly no. Its unpleasant enough to deal with someone sending me a complaint about one of my guildmates but being an officer its my job to deal with it. On the other hand it must be reasonable. Lets say I get 2 KS complaints. One is off an orc pawn in Gfay and the other is the AC in OOT. Obviously both parties are greived but the AC would be the only one I was concerned with unless it was a repeated KS by the orc pawn person. There is only so far you can hold a guild responsible for its members before its forcing them to remove a person just so they can go on stuff. What if the person we want gone happens to be the GL's nefew? Not pretty and now you have alot of pissed off people. I would rather keep it to individual faults myself.<br>
<br>
New Raids - There are times that I lay awake at night regretting volunteering to run CoG. I'm figuring its cause I'm a woman that people ignore my shouts. I've accepted that now though, but there are other days, like when we were standing over Vox's corpse that I was really proud to have had the guts to stand up and say &quot;sure, I'll try&quot; *note - not &quot;sure I can do it&quot;* As to opening CoG up to more raids, it wont be by Flar and I sorry. Our baby is crawling and pulling herself up on furniture now, and leading even dragons is a major hardship right now. To be honest - yeah sure we have the people to do it BUT, the people here are not used to working with eachother, dont understand eachothers habbits, quirks and manerisms. Some things that their guild puts up with, others wont (like me with emote spamming and swearing). When style gets cramped and you're not in familiar territory things start going wrong.<br>
<br>
Yes bravery is a big problem. Gating out of Hate cause &quot;omg I'm gonna die on break in&quot; is not the brightest of tactics but that person learned the lesson. People stopping at Naggy's door going &quot;I ain't dyin one more time, forget it&quot; well heh, I still remember you. Expanding to do more raids could be asking for a hefty corpse recovery. I'm just as curious as any cat out there adn am more than happy to explore, but most aren't. Most stay with whats familiar cause its exactly that, familiar. Good luck to anyone starting up DN, SG, SC or any other raid. I'll be the first to admit I wont envy your job and you know I'd stand behind and support you as much as possible though.<br>
<br>
I took too long.<br>
