<br>
I have not attended a CoG raid since then, but I have quietly followed the progress.<br>
<br>
I've also had the pleasure of being on a raid with Stone and many others, whose names I have seen here.  My heartiest recomendations to these people.<br>
<br>
As for a raid enforcer.  Good dea that has workable solutions, however, it will turn into a bureaucratic nightmare on you.  You'll get smashed with the following:<br>
&quot;Why does wallywanka get to be enforcer?&quot;<br>
&quot;Slaphappy Dominatrix removed me for no reason!&quot;<br>
&quot;What a suck up!&quot;<br>
&quot;Children telling other children what to do!&quot;<br>
&quot;She is just gettin in good with the leaders.&quot;<br>
You will see such assinine bullshit concerning some one with this kind of power.  whats more, if you intend to have the Enforcer &quot;tell on&quot; the offender, the leader is not going to be able to focus and concentrate on far more important matters at hand.  Like leading the damn raid.<br>
<br>
The problem is respect and discipline.  In all the raids CoG has had problems on, I have many friends who have attended, it has been few mistakes my leaders, and more about raid discipline and respect or lack there of for the commander.<br>
<br>
Why is it, that guilds that raid dragons on their own have this sort of thing ironed out and have so few problems?  Experience and having worked together before, OR, they respect the Command body enough to comply with each command straight away.<br>
<br>
The members are more concerned with their team mates than their socialite standings and just how many people they can have looking at them at any given time.  They are  not more concerned with popularity contests and witty assinine comments.  These types of people, that do the crap I just listed,  are a very real reason I do not set foot onto CoG raids anymore.  Sick to death of people who either cannot read, refused to read, or are just plain too damn stupid to follow commands. People more concerned with &quot;why dont I get to roll&quot;  and &quot;this is taking to long!&quot;  &quot;When do we roll?&quot;  &quot;huh huh when do we lotto&quot;,  I got much better things to do with my time than babysit several 20somethings without a clue.<br>
<br>
Now then.<br>
<br>
How to fix it.<br>
For your next series of raids, invite 1 rep from each guild you think will attend. They are observers and are NOT grouped together. These people simply write down the names of the people who do not follow commands, who break the rules, who shout, or spam or in general cause disruption and are a liability to the raid itself.  These lists are then compiled by the management body after the raid, any name found twice or more on this list, is publicly named here on this forum, and forthwith removed from ANY future CoG raid of any type.  You can warn this person one time, if you like, personally if you have not read or cannot understand the rules for CoG raids you neither deserve a spot, nor are you capable of handling it anyway.  Learn discipline, it ain't hard.<br>
<br>
Do this on 2 raids, and yer discipline problems will be fully resolved.<br>
<br>
